SIMPLE: indict
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indict
<hw>In*dict"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*d⟦imac⟧t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Indicted</conjf>
<pr>(⟦icr⟧n*d⟦imac⟧t"⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Indicting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>enditen</ets>. See
<er>Indite</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To write; to compose; to dictate; to indite.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To appoint publicly or by authority; to proclaim or
announce.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am told shall have no Lent <qex>indicted</qex> this year.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To charge with a crime, in due form
of law, by the finding or presentment of a grand jury; to bring an
indictment against; <as>as, to <ex>indict</ex> a man for arson</as>. It
is the peculiar province of a grand jury to <ex>indict</ex>, as it is of
a house of representatives to <contr>impeach</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indictable</ent>⟦br⟧
